postcontent:
A very clean, well cared for Kahr PM9 subcompact, black slide 9mm handgun for sale.

Shoots extremely tight groups for a subcompact (I typically shoot 5-7" groups at 20 feet, and I'm not the best shooter in town by far).  I really like this gun, and if life circumstances were otherwise I'd be keeping it.

Has Kahr custom polished feedramp and other tuning for rapid fire reliability.  Comes with XS big dot sights professionally installed and calibrated, 3 clips (2 long, 1 short), a custom Kydex concealed carry holster (Comp-Tac 2 O'Clock, right hand), original case and paperwork.

Trigger pull is very consistent, and with the custom factory work this has an even smoother delivery if that was possible.  

If you're looking for a comfortable all-day-carry subcompact that packs a serious punch and is easily controlled and exceptionally accurate, this is the gun for you.

title: For Sale:  Heckler & Koch H&K HK45 Compact Ergo Grip (HK745031A5)
postcontent:
HK45 COMPACT
Smaller in length and height than the standard HK45, the HK45 Compact (HK45C) uses a slim-line grip profile, otherwise is nearly identical in features to the full-size HK45.

Like the HK45, the HK45 Compact was developed as a possible candidate for the Joint Combat Pistol (JCP) and Combat Pistol (CP) programs administered by the U.S. military in their search for a new service handgun. These programs were suspended before completion and no pistols were selected.

The HK45 Compact uses an HK proprietary O-ring barrel for precise barrel-to-slide lockup and optimal accuracy. HK45 barrels are made using the famous HK cold-hammer forging process for superior performance.

Using HK’s unique internal mechanical recoil reduction system reduces the recoil forces imparted to the weapon and shooter by as much as 30%, improving shooter control during rapid firing and increasing component service life.

Capable of firing standard .45 ACP ball through +P ammunition, the HK45 Compact has an 8-round magazine capacity but can also use 10-round magazines, including those designed for the full-size HK45. The HK45 combines the accuracy, modularity, reliability, and minimum 20,000 round service life of the renowned USP45 Compact with the improved ergonomics of the P2000 series pistols. HK45 Compacts can be also be fitted with threaded barrels for use with muzzle mounted sound suppressors.

Each HK45 Compact comes standard with an extra backstrap for a custom fit for each shooter’s hand.

Both the HK45 Compact and full-size HK45 use an improved USP-style control lever, a combination safety and decocking lever. The control lever is frame mounted and is quickly accessible; it has a positive stop and returns to the “fire” position after decocking.

By using the modular approach to the internal components first pioneered by HK on the USP, the control lever function of the HK45 and HK45C can be switched from the left to the right side of the pistol to accommodate left-handed shooters (additional parts required). Left and right mounted control levers provide safety and/or decocking functions as required and can be fitted to the pistol simply by changing parts. For true ambidextrous use, a control lever can also be mounted on both sides of the pistol if required.

Well-suited for personal defense use, the HK45C is available in, or can be converted to, a wide variety of variants that use different trigger firing modes, including double action/single action (DA/SA) and DAO (double action only). The DAO mode uses the unique Heckler & Koch LEM (Law Enforcement Modification) firing system, providing an enhanced double action trigger pull.

Extensively tested and operationally proven, the HK45C is currently being assembled from U.S. and German made components at HK’s American manufacturing facility in Newington, New Hampshire.

Key features and system characteristics::
Integral MIL-STD-1913 (Picatinny) rail molded into the polymer frame dust cover for mounting lights, laser aimers, and other accessories
ERGO (HK45 full-size) and slim-line (HK45 Compact) grip profiles with user replaceable grip panels to adjust the feel and grip circumference of the weapon to suit individual operator hand size and shooting preference
8-round metal magazine is standard for the HK45C, common high-capacity (10 rounds) that fit both the HK45 and HK45C also available
Ambidextrous controls with dual slide releases and enlarged magazine release
Uses the proven modified Browning linkless recoil operating system
O-ring barrel for precise barrel-to-slide lockup and better accuracy
Polygonal rifling for longer barrel life and increased accuracy
Improved ergonomic control levers (safety and/or decocking)
Low profile drift adjustable 3-dot sights
Contoured and radiused slide with forward slide (grasping) grooves and anti-glare longitudinal ribs
Black polymer frame

This is a pretty rare gun. If you have ever held a colt mustang or something similar then you have a pretty good idea of how this gun will feel in your hand. It has a very similar look and feel to a mini 1911 in 380 acp. The gun has a stainless finish and ivory colored grips. The grips are original and are in good shape. I have cleaned it up about as good as it can get and you should be able to see the finish issues in the photos. After I saw and felt my first one I knew I wanted one, but couldn't afford it the first time around. I bought this gun from a customer last winter, but I now need money more than this gun. I would be happy to show it to you anytime I am available and I guarantee the gun to work. It will feed hollow point ammo just fine but I have had trouble trying to feed Hornady Critical Defense through it because the polymer tips will jam against the feed ramp and will cause the gun to jam. However I have also shot regular hollow points and fmj's through it and they feed fine with no issue. The magazine capacity is 7. The gun features a single action only, and has a safety. The gun is lightweight and very comfortable to carry and hold in your hand. The recoil is very light and wouldn't be too much for even a beginner shooter or a female that hates recoil. The PT22 is often viewed as a Taurus copy of the Beretta 21 Bobcat due to having a similar "tip up" barrel. In fact this small pistol is very different in design and function from the Beretta. The PT22 is a cast steel frame and slide, manufactured in Florida, USA. It has a spur-less hammer, and a long but smooth double action only (DAO) trigger. The "tip up" barrel is useful in that the first round may be chambered directly into the barrel, and the operator does not have to "pull back" or "rack" the slide. Retracting the slide is difficult due to the heavy spring required in this blow-back action. The grip feel of the PT22 is "fat", and fills a normal-sized hand.

title: For Sale:  Complete .223/5.56/300 BLK Bolt Carrier Group. $135
postcontent:
We only have two left! 
Brand New .223/5.56/300 BLK Complete Bolt Carrier Groups. Retail is $185 our price is $135! Ea. 
REDACTED
 They are made in the USA and are superior to Mil-spec. These are full auto bolts and will work in AR15s, M4s and M16s. They come completely assembled ready to drop in.  
These are the same BCG's that New Frontier Armory uses at their range for all of their full auto rifles and they run thousands of rounds w/o any issues. 
A break down of the Specs are below.

Bolt Control Group Info from the Manufacture:
Changes vs milspec: rake and fillet cuts at the bolt head, heat treating, chamfering changes, a proprietary spring and polymer insert under the extractor

Material as follows: 
Carrier, Gas key, Cam pin, Ejector: 8620 or 4130/40
Extractor: tool steel & MIM'd
Bolt: 9310 or 4130/4140
Firing pin: 400 series stainless

Everything but the firing pin and extractor are carbo nitrided to allow a hard surface and more malleable core to help avoid cracking and still reduce wear. We have the extractor MIM'd (metal injection molded). This requires reducing hardness rather than increasing hardness. MIM'ing is very reliable when done correctly with updated technology in the US, less expensive and provides a superior part in the end. Did you know that the desert eagle 50 cal has almost all internal parts MIM'd? We have actually tested to destruction and found the MIM part to be more robust than the machined part. 

Some feel that the mil-spec carpenter 158 material is the only correct material to use on a bolt since it is called out in the mil-spec. They couldn't be more wrong. Many companies make look alikes to c158 with the same specs to the carpenter 158 but cannot sell it for military contracts because it doesn't say carpenter in front of it. This has nothing at all to do with performance or quality. It has to do with influence. Look at the specs for c158, E150, 9310 and 4130. You will find very little difference among them other than yield strength. Yield is not at issue in a linear function like a bolt carrier group experiences. 

Carbo-nitriding was not accepted in the mil-spec primarily because it required a cyanide process in the 1940s and 1950s. This is no longer true and provides superior performance and longevity.

Many purchasers want a magnetic particle inspection of the bolt. This is the MPI mark on some bolts. The problem with this is that: 
Magnetic particle inspection does no good on an un-fired part. There won't be any cracks to detect. The purpose of MP testing is to detect cracks after a proof load is fired through a gun at much higher pressures. No one that I know of actually proof load tests individual bolts. Many mark their bolts MP and if called on it, say it means manganese phosphate. I won't allow that kind of deceit. Unless there is a true MPI / HP test done, it’s a waste of time/money. Even then, they only test one out of a batch of parts. We can get them tested, but we'd obviously have to add the cost into the parts."
